data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions change overload resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)`** instead of **`Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime (or may fail to compile depending on context).

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both ensure the expression tree uses the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is representable in expression trees. The same issue can affect `.Reverse()` on arrays (resolves to the in-place `Span` version) — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` there too.
